Washington (2008): Female Socialization: How Daughters Affect Their Legislator Fathersâ Voting on Womenâs Issues

Motivation

  • How do children affect their parentsâ behavior? Previous examples on peer effects by neighbours or friends.
  • Shift in beliefs translates to a shift in behaviours.
  • Parenting daughters (versus sons) shifts voting behavior on womenâs issues in a more liberal direction.

Dataset

Legislator Characteristics and Voting Behavior

  • The dataset explores the relationship between legislator characteristics and voting behavior, focusing on:
    • Number of daughters
    • Number of children
    • Liberal voting patterns (e.g., NOW Score, AAUW Score)

Dataset

Key Variables

  1. Dependent Variables:
    • NOW Score: National Organization for Women voting score.
    • AAUW Score: American Association of University Women voting score.
  2. Independent Variables:
    • Number of Daughters: Count of female children.
    • Number of Children: Total children in the family.
    • Demographics: Party affiliation, race, religion, gender, age.

Experiment

Main results

An increase of one daughter in the legislatorâs family leads to a 2.3 point score increase on voting for womenâs issues.

\[ \begin{align*} \text{Score}_{i} &= \beta_{0} + \beta_{1} \cdot \text{Number of daughters}_{i} \\ &+ \beta_{2} \cdot \text{Number of daughters}_{i} \\ &+ \beta_{2}\cdot \text{Number of sons}_{i} + e_{i} \end{align*} \]

Controls: Female, White, Republican, Age, Service length, Religion, Democratic vote share in distric. Region, and number of children fixed effects.
